When you tilt the sensor 30° to the left, two things need to agree:
The accelerometer measures the changed direction of gravity and says: "I tilted left."
The gyroscope measures the rotation speed and tells GTSAM: "We are currently rotating to the left." From this GTSAM builds the current orientation R(t).
GTSAM then uses R(t) to calculate how much of the accelerometer signal is gravity and subtracts it. What remains should be zero if you are not actually moving.

If the gyroscope sign is wrong:
The gyroscope says "rotating right" while the accelerometer says "tilting left". GTSAM builds the wrong R(t) and subtracts gravity in the wrong direction. Instead of cancelling out, the gravity component doubles. GTSAM then thinks the sensor is accelerating hard to the side, integrates that into velocity and it explodes.

-> Also the LIDAR Data being this slow is not good, because the LIDAR will recalibrate the IMU, but can't if it'S so much off. 
